{
  id: "01000000000D0000",
  group: "",
  order_index: 6,
  filename: "13_applied_energistics_2",
  title: "Applied Energistics 2",
  default_quest_shape: "",
  default_hide_dependency_lines: false,
  quests: [
    {
      id: "02000000000E0000",
      title: "You will be Assimilated",
      x: 18.67,
      y: 2.67,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "03000000000E0000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:interface"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  &lME Interfaces&r are the doorways to the ME system from machines and devices in the world.  Items can be piped into it from hoppers or other means, and they will be assimilated into the ME storage cells if there is sufficient room.", "", "  They can also be configured to buffer certain items, allowing hoppers, pipes, etc. to passively pull from the ME system.  Place the items you wish to buffer in the top row of the &lInterface&r's GUI.  You can adjust the quantity of the items by having the same number of items in-hand, so if you wanted a full stack of coal, you'd place a full stack of coal in a slot in the top row.  To clear the buffer's configuration, simply left click on the respective item in the top row.", "", "Note: The output buffer (items going out of the ME system) shares the same inventory space as the input buffer, so be sure to leave at least one slot clear if you want to use the same interface for both input and output.", "", "  More features of the Interface will be covered in other quests where they are relevant.", "", "Tip:  ME Interfaces also have a multipart  or \"flat panel\" version.  You can toggle between the two types by simply tossing the Interface into a crafting grid by itself.  However, this version will not power the device it is attached to, nor will it connect to devices other than what it is attached to."],
      icon: "ae2:interface",
      dependencies: ["0200000001510000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "04000000000E0000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:interface",
          count: 4
        },
        {
          id: "04000000000E0001",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:cable_interface",
          count: 4
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000C70000",
      title: "I See a Pattern Here...",
      x: 26,
      y: 0,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000C70000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:pattern_encoding_terminal"
        },
        {
          id: "0300000000C70001",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:blank_pattern"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  &lME Pattern Terminals&r are used to program &lCrafting Patterns&r and &lProcessing Patterns&r, the former being used by &lMolecular Assemblers&r to perform crafting table recipes, and the latter being used to perform recipes done by other blocks and machines (including furnaces and brewing stands, but mainly machines from other mods).", "", "  The Terminal's GUI is broken up into three parts:", "", " * The &l&oME Grid&r at the top to allow access to ingredients for recipes,", "", " * The &l&oPattern Grid&r group in the lower left and middle is where you'll be setting therecipes for patterns, and", "", " * The &l&oPattern Queue&r group in the lower right is where you'll put patterns to be programmed and where you'll retrieved patterns that have been programmed.", "", "  Instructions to program the two types of patterns are covered later in the questline."],
      icon: "ae2:pattern_encoding_terminal",
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000C70000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:blank_pattern",
          count: 64
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000C80000",
      title: "See Pea You",
      x: 26,
      y: 2,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000C80000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:crafting_unit"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  The &l&oCrafting Processing Unit&r is a multiblock construction that is essential to AE2's autocrafting.  In essence, it is responsible for coordinating the various machines connected to the ME system so that they can craft one or more items from a single request.", "", "  They are constructed in a solid cuboid, in any arrangement, of its component blocks.", "", "  &lCrafting Units&r are a core crafting ingredient for the other component blocks of the Crafting CPU multiblock.  They can used as filler blocks, too, but otherwise don't have any function.", "", ""],
      icon: "ae2:crafting_unit",
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000C80000",
          type: "random",
          table_id: 360287970189705216
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000ED0000",
      title: "Networking Tools",
      x: 18,
      y: 1,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000ED0000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:certus_quartz_wrench"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  The &lQuartz Wrench&r is used to safely pry off most AE2 devices and cables, and can interact with some devices (such as the ME Interface) in a special way.  To pry off a device or cable, Sneak + Use the wrench while looking at the target.  Careful! Sometimes they can fly off a fair distance.", "", "Note: There's no difference between the Certus and Nether Quartz wrenches in terms of functionality.", "", "  The &lNetwork Tool&r is a modified Quartz Wrench that can open a GUI on a cable or connected device to view the status of all connected cables/devices on the network, right up to the ME Controller.  It however loses some of the special functions that a Quartz Wrench has."],
      icon: "ae2:certus_quartz_wrench",
      dependencies: ["0200000001510000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000ED0000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:network_tool"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000EE0000",
      title: "Harmless",
      x: 0,
      y: 8,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000EE0000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:charged_staff"
        },
        {
          id: "0300000000EE0001",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:entropy_manipulator"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  The &lCharged Staff&r is a weapon that deals damage comparable to that of an Iron Sword.  It differs from the sword, however, in that it consumes energy instead of durability.  It also deals magic damage instead of physical, which means it can bypass most armors.  A notable exception are Witches, who have a bit of magic resistance instead of armor.", "", "  The &lEntropy Manipulator&r can set fires to blocks and mobs at the cost of energy.  Right click on a block, left click on a mob.", "", "  Both devices may be recharged in a &lCharger&r."],
      icon: "ae2:charged_staff",
      dependencies: ["02000000014F0000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000EE0000",
          type: "random",
          table_id: 360287970189705216
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000EF0000",
      title: "I See What You Did There...",
      x: 27,
      y: 4,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000EF0000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:crafting_monitor"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  &lCrafting Monitors&r are an optional block that will visually display the current top-level task (what you ordered).", "", " Only one of these may be in the entire multiblock.", "", ""],
      icon: "ae2:crafting_monitor",
      dependencies: ["0200000000C80000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000EF0000",
          type: "random",
          table_id: 360287970189705216
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000F00000",
      title: "Download More Wam",
      x: 25,
      y: 4,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000F00000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:1k_crafting_storage"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  &lCrafting Storage Units&r are like the RAM of your computer, allowing for larger recipes or larger batch orders to go through.  Shouuld there be an insufficent amount of CSU's in the multiblock, the crafting request will refuse to start.  Should this happen, you can either reduce the number of requested items in the batch, add more CSU's to the multiblock, or swap out CSU's with a higher tier version.", "", "  You must have at least one CSU in the multiblock."],
      icon: "ae2:1k_crafting_storage",
      dependencies: ["0200000000C80000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000F00000",
          type: "random",
          table_id: 360287970189705216
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000F10000",
      title: "See Sea Pea You",
      x: 26,
      y: 6,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000F10000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:crafting_accelerator"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  &lCrafting Co-Processing Units&r are the task coordinators of the multiblock.  A task is defined as a single crafting operation, and each Unit can initiate a single task by moving the requested ingredients to the appropriate ME Interface.  More CCPU's in the multiblock mean more tasks can be started at the same time, although a single CCPU is still capable of doing different types of tasks.", "", "  For example, 4 assemblers are attached to an ME interface.  All 4 assemblers have the potential of performing the same type of crafting task.  With a single CCPU, 1 assembler will be started, then another, then another, then finally the last assembler.  With 4 CCPU's, all 4 assemblers will be started at the same time.  For small crafting recipes, the difference usually doesn't matter since the CCPU's can switch between tasks at a fast rate.  Only on the very large recipes does adding more CCPU's make an impact."],
      icon: "ae2:crafting_accelerator",
      dependencies: ["0200000000C80000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000F10000",
          type: "random",
          table_id: 360287970189705216
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000F30000",
      title: "IKEA Worker of the Year",
      x: 23,
      y: 4,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000F30000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:molecular_assembler"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  The &lMolecular Assembler&r is a machine that will perform a craft according to a &lCrafting Pattern&r placed in the slot above the output slot.  Items piped into the Assembler will go to the correct location and the result will be automatically pushed into an adjacent inventory.  Crafting performed in this matter is referred to as &opassive&r or &ocontinous auto-crafting&r, since crafting will continously be done so long as the Assembler is fed enough ingredients.", "", "Tip:  When trying to push the result, the &lAssembler&r will start with the bottom, then the top, then the sides.  Keep this in mind when doing passive auto-crafting, as it can push into its input hopper.", "", "  The &lAssembler&r must be powered through a cable or another connected AE2, but it does not take up a channel."],
      icon: "ae2:molecular_assembler",
      dependencies: ["0200000000F50000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000F30000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:molecular_assembler",
          count: 4
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000F40000",
      title: "Crafting, On Demand.",
      x: 24,
      y: 7,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000F40000",
          type: "item",
          item: "minecraft:oak_planks",
          count: 4
        }
      ],
      description: ["  This is it, the culmination of several hours of reading walls of text that could keep out the Mongols during all of the Ming Dynasty.", "", "  Everything learned thus far is put to use to achieve &o&lon-demand auto-crafting&r. We will start of with crafting table recipes before moving on to the slightly more complex machine crafting.", "", "  First of all, make sure you have a functioning &lCrafting Processing Unit&r multiblock connected to the ME system (including an ME drive with at least one Storage Cell in it), and sufficient power for everything.", "", "  Place a &lME Interface&r somewhere and  connect it to the rest of the ME system.", "", "  Then, place a &lMolecular Assembler&r on top or otherwise adjacent to the interface.", "", "  Program a &lCrafting Pattern&r for &lWood Planks&r (or another simple crafting recipe) and place the pattern in a slot in the bottom row of the &lInterface&r's GUI.", "", "  Finally, &o&lTest&r the installation by interacting with any suitable &lME Terminal&r or variant.  The item you programmed the Pattern to (such as our wood planks) should show up in the grid with a friendly \"CRAFT\" label over it.", "", "Tip:  If you already have wood planks in the system, you should pull them all out or use a different recipe.", "", "Tip:  If the programmed item still doesn't show up in the grid, check your connections, and check to see you programmed the Pattern correctly.  Too often does a Processing Pattern get made instead of the inteded Crafting Pattern.", "", "  Left click on the item, the crafting request GUI should pop up, allowing you to specify how many items to craft.  We'll just go with 1 for this test.", "", "  The next GUI that pops up will show you how many bytes is required to process the \"job,\" and all of the ingredients available and any ingredients that need to be crafted.  Click \"START\" to tell the system to begin crafting!", "", "Note: If if an error message pops up stating that \"No processors are available!\" it probably means you need more Crafting Storage Units.", ""],
      icon: "ae2:logic_processor",
      dependencies: ["0200000000F10000", "0200000000F30000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000F40000",
          type: "random",
          table_id: 360287970189705216
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000F50000",
      title: "Crafting Patterns",
      x: 23,
      y: 2,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000F50000",
          type: "checkmark",
          title: "checkbox"
        }
      ],
      description: ["&lCrafting Patterns&r are relatively straight forward to program.", "", "  First, ensure that the button on the right hand side looks like a crafting table, if it does not, then press it to switch it over.", "", "  Place the ingredients in the &l&oPattern Grid&r like you would a normal crafting grid, and the resulting item should appear in the slot to the immediate right.  (If it doesn't, check your recipe).", "", "  Then, make sure you have at least one &lBlank Pattern&r in the top slot of the &l&oPattern Queue&r and press the button with a down arrow to program it.", "", "Tip:  You'd normally would want the ore dictionary enabled for patterns, unless there's a specific reason why one type of copper (for example) is extra special.", "", "Tip:  Patterns can be overwritten if left in the bottom slot of the &l&oPattern Queue&r", ""],
      icon: "minecraft:crafting_table",
      dependencies: ["0200000000C70000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000F50000",
          type: "random",
          table_id: 360287970189705216
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000F60000",
      title: "Processing Patterns",
      x: 29,
      y: 2,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000F60000",
          type: "checkmark",
          title: "checkbox"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  &lProcessing Patterns&r are programmed in a similar fashion to &lCrafting Patterns&r with a few key differences.", "", "  First of which is that the order of the items in the &l&oPattern Grid&r no longer matter, these will all be pushed to a recipient machine (or inventory!) at the same time.", "", "  Second of which is that you can specify up to three different result (or output) items on the right side of the &l&oPattern Grid&r.  These are items that the ME system will expect to find after some time, and must be pushed into the network by hoppers or pipes via &lME Interfaces&r, or be pulled in by an &lImport Bus&r.", "", "  Lastly, you can specify a different amount of items (up to a full stack) per slot in either the input or output sides of the &l&oPattern Grid", "", "&4&l&oWarning!&r A crafting task will look for &oexactly&r the same amount of items you specified in the output slots of the Pattern Grid.  If it cannot find the item (for example Thermal Foundation's &lSlag&r) then the crafting task will be listed as incomplete or still \"in-progress.\"  You'll have to be clever to get such items to autocraft correctly.&r.."],
      icon: "minecraft:furnace",
      dependencies: ["0200000000C70000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000F60000",
          type: "random",
          table_id: 360287970189705216
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000F70000",
      title: "Wheels on the Bus",
      x: 21,
      y: 6,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000F70000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:export_bus"
        },
        {
          id: "0300000000F70001",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:import_bus"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  Aside from &lME Interfaces&r, there are also &lImport Busses&r and &lExport Busses&r.", "", "  Both types should be fairly self-explanitory:", "", " The &lImport Bus&r pulls items from an attached inventory or machine &ointo&r the ME System.  It can be configured to pull only a certain type of item through its GUI.", "", " The &lExport Bus&r pushes items into an inventory or machine that it is attached to.  It must be told which items to export and how many it should try to push at a time (similar to how the ME Interface operates).", "", "  Both Busses start off with only 1 available slot, but you can give them up to 2 &lCapacity Cards&r to increase by 4 slots each for each card.", "", "  Both Busses are multipart constructions, and are easily installed by placing them on the inventory/machine that they will be importing/exporting."],
      icon: "ae2:import_bus",
      dependencies: ["02000000000E0000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000F70000",
          type: "random",
          table_id: 360287970189705216
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000F80000",
      title: "Dramatic Pause",
      x: 22,
      y: 8,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000F80000",
          type: "checkmark",
          title: "checkbox"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  By now, you should have successfully made &lWood Planks&r from demanding it through an &lME Terminal&r.  If not, check your connections (A &lNetwork Tool&r may help), check your power supply, and check your &lCrafting Pattern&r for any flaws.  If you're still having problems doing your first autocraft, then feel free to drop by the Enigmatica Discord and ask for help.", "", "&9&nhttps://discord.gg/HnWNd7X&r", "", ""],
      icon: "minecraft:cookie",
      dependencies: ["0200000000F40000"]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000F90000",
      title: "Scribble Scribble",
      x: 28,
      y: 7,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000F90000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:printed_silicon"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  This final quest in the autocrafting line will teach you the basics of interfacing machines to get them to do autocrafting for you.  For our example, we'll automate the &lInscriber&r, which is a good machine to automate since you will be needing quite a few of the different processors as you progress further through AE2.", "", "  You will need:", "1x &lME Interface&r", "1x &lImport Bus&r", "1x &lInscriber&r", "1x &lInscriber Silicon Press&r", "1x &lBlank Pattern&r", "", "  Place the &lInscriber&r.", "", "  Place the &lME Interface&r on top of the Inscriber (or anywhere adjacent).", "", "  Place the &lImport Bus&r on the bottom of the Inscriber (or anywhere adjacent).", "", "  Connect the &lME Interface&r and the &lImport Bus&r to the ME system.", "", "  Place the &lInscriber Silicon Press&r inside of the Inscriber, and place a piece of Silicon in the center slot to verify that it has power and is functioning.", "", "Hint: The panel variant of the ME Interface won't supply power, so you may have to attach a cable to the side of the Inscriber.", "", "  Program a &lProcessing Pattern&r (remember, it has a Furnace icon) on the ME Pattern Terminal.  1 Silicon as the input, 1 Printed Silicon as the Output.", "", "  Place the programmed Processing Pattern into the &lME Interface&r, and &l&oTest&r the setup by requesting a Printed Silicon from the ME System (Like you did with the previous quest)."],
      icon: "ae2:engineering_processor",
      dependencies: ["0200000000F10000", "0200000001490000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000F90000",
          type: "random",
          table_id: 360287970189705216
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000FA0000",
      title: "Pregnant Pause",
      x: 30,
      y: 8,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000FA0000",
          type: "checkmark",
          title: "Complete"
        }
      ],
      description: ["  That's it.  That's the basics to automating a machine with AE2.  The following are tips, hints, and a general summary of what happens.", "", "&l  Crafting Patterns&r or &lProcessing Patterns&r go into the &lME Interfaces&r, when a crafting request is made by the &l&oCPU multiblock&r, it'll have the ME Interface push the ingredients into an adjacent inventory.", "", "Tip:  If you're one for compact builds, you can right click an &lME Interface&r block with a &lQuartz Wrench&r to tell it to push only into a certain direction.  Otherwise, the Interface will pick a side at random.  You can also use the panel version of the Interface to limit to just one side, but remember that it won't supply power nor act as a cable.", "", "  Use &lImport Busses&r to pull crafted items from machines into the ME system. If the machine can push items, you can instead have it push into an ME Interface (which can be the same one that has the Processing Pattern).", "", "  Machines that need a Catalyst, Tool, or Fuel (such as furnaces) should have that item pushed into them by an &lExport Bus&r, have the tool left in them, or be maintained by other means.  Some blocks, such as furnaces, are picky about which side the items are pushed in and taken.  Furnaces have input at the top, fuel at any side, and output at the bottom.", "", "  Crafting tasks are marked as \"success\" if the product of a Crafting Pattern or Processing Pattern is pushed into the system from &oany&r ME Interface or Import Bus.  This only happens if the task was started by a CPU, however."],
      icon: "minecraft:cake",
      dependencies: ["0200000000F90000"],
      rewards: [
        {
          id: "0400000000FA0000",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:engineering_processor",
          count: 8
        },
        {
          id: "0400000000FA0001",
          type: "item",
          item: "ae2:logic_processor",
          count: 8
        },
        {
          id: "0400000000FA0002",
          type: "item",
          item: "minecraft:cake"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      id: "0200000000FB0000",
      title: "Just a Few for the Road",
      x: 10,
      y: 8,
      tasks: [
        {
          id: "0300000000FB0000",
